      Bitcoin flash crash
   =20
 =20

The US has about a dozen stock exchanges. Each stock trades on each stock e=
xchange. Every so often the price of a stock on one exchange will be slight=
ly lower than the price on another exchange. Books=C2=A0have been written a=
bout this fact, and people have made long and lucrative careers from it.
But we are talking about small differences=C2=A0in the grand scheme of thin=
gs. If I were to tell you =E2=80=9CApple Inc. stock has been trading at $17=
4 per share on the NYSE Arca exchange for the last hour, but it=E2=80=99s b=
een trading at $175 on Nasdaq the whole time,=E2=80=9D you would not believ=
e me; that is barely even a coherent sentence. For one thing, there are rul=
es to prevent that. But also, I mean, this stuff is all on computers, and t=
hese prices are all visible, and there are people who have lucrative career=
s noticing any differences. If Apple was trading at $174 on Arca and at $17=
5 on Nasdaq, those people would buy it on Arca and sell it on Nasdaq, makin=
g a risk-free instantaneous profit. And so many of them would do this so qu=
ickly that the prices would more or less instantly converge.
Again, at a certain scale =E2=80=94 for the arbitrageurs who make a career =
of this stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0this is=C2=A0not true; there are milliseconds =
when you can buy at $174.99 one place and sell at $175 another place and ma=
ke a quick profit. But at human scales it is true enough; there are not=C2=
=A0hours=C2=A0when=C2=A0you can buy at $174 one place and sell at $175 anot=
her.
But that=E2=80=99s only true because there are a lot of those arbitrageurs =
with a lot of capital and fast computers, and because a lot of technologica=
l and regulatory work has gone into making sure that all of those arbitrage=
urs can connect to all the stock exchanges and see their prices and move th=
eir capital quickly to whatever exchange has cheap stock for sale. You coul=
d imagine a different system. You could imagine a system where NYSE Arca is=
 downtown and Nasdaq is in midtown and you have to take a horse and buggy b=
etween them to trade, and you can=E2=80=99t use the phone, and there=E2=80=
=99s just one of you; then maybe prices would diverge by dollars for hours.=
 That=E2=80=99s not too hard to imagine =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was roughly true =
100 years ago, though stocks traded on fewer venues back then =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it does not really reflect our modern computerized markets.
And then there=E2=80=99s Bitcoin!

The price of Bitcoin against Tether=E2=80=99s USDT stablecoin fell to as lo=
w as $8,900 on BitMEX late Monday, while the largest cryptocurrency was tra=
ding above $66,000 on rival venues. The price of Bitcoin on the exchange qu=
ickly recovered and has been trading in-line with the rest of the market si=
nce.
A spokesperson for BitMEX said the company investigated the incident and fo=
und evidence of =E2=80=9Caggressive selling behavior involving a very small=
 number of accounts that exceeded expected market ranges,=E2=80=9D adding t=
hat its systems had operated normally and all user funds are safe.
BitMEX is =E2=80=9Cinvestigating potential misconduct by traders on our Bit=
coin-USDT Spot market,=E2=80=9D the exchange said in=C2=A0a post=C2=A0on th=
e X social-media platform on Tuesday. The exchange does not employ internal=
 market makers and the orders to sell Bitcoin =E2=80=9Cwere simply too big =
and frequent for independent market makers and other traders to react to,=
=E2=80=9D according to the same post. The incident had no impact on BitMEX=
=E2=80=99s derivatives markets and no liquidations were triggered by it, th=
e post added.=C2=A0

The best guess appears to be that this was one big whale, or perhaps a few,=
 dumping Bitcoin steadily over a few hours:
=E2=80=9CSomeone just dumped 400+ BTC over 2 hours in 10-50 BTC clips on th=
e XBTUSDT pair on Bitmex eating 30%+ slippage. They must've lost $4m+ at le=
ast,=E2=80=9D pseudonymous crypto community member =E2=80=9Csyq=E2=80=9D wr=
ote. =E2=80=9CI'm guessing that they're done (for now?). Total volume so fa=
r is just shy of 1,000 BTC over 3.5 hours with a low of $8,900. Now BitMEX =
have disabled withdrawals,=E2=80=9D they added.
The exceptionally low prices did not persist uninterrupted=C2=A0for hours a=
t a time or anything, but there seems to have been a pretty intense 10-minu=
te period of=C2=A0low prices, and in any case each=C2=A0time=C2=A0this whal=
e dumped 10 to 50 Bitcoin at a time, it got prices far lower than the print=
s on any other exchange.=C2=A0
And, you know, if I were making markets in Bitcoin on Coinbase, and I notic=
ed that Bitcoin was selling for $8,900 on BitMEX, I would simply get myself=
 over to BitMEX and start bidding, like, $9,000 for Bitcoin. That=E2=80=99s=
 free money!
Why didn=E2=80=99t anyone? Part of the answer is probably that they did; th=
is gap eventually closed, though from BitMEX=E2=80=99s posting it seems tha=
t the gap closed more because the whale stopped selling than because anyone=
 stepped in to buy.=C2=A0
But another part of the answer is that crypto exchanges are fundamentally d=
ifferent businesses from stock exchanges. In the US, if you buy stock on a =
stock exchange, you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0send the money to the stock exchange=
. You send the money to the seller (and the seller sends the stock to you) =
through a clearinghouse; there=E2=80=99s one main clearinghouse for all US =
stock trades, and every exchange and broker is hooked up to it. If you are =
an arbitrageur looking to buy $100 million worth of stock, you don=E2=80=99=
t have to park $100 million at=C2=A0each of the 12 exchanges so you can tra=
de on whichever one has the lowest price. You park $100 million at your one=
 brokerage firm, and the broker handles settlement for you wherever you act=
ually execute the trade.
  [1]

In crypto, it is the norm for exchanges to hold your money for you. One thi=
ng that this means is that there is a long and comical history of exchanges=
 losing or stealing that money. Another, related thing that it means is tha=
t traders have to evaluate the credit risk of exchanges: You do not want to=
 deposit $100 million on an exchange that will go and lose or steal=C2=A0it=
.
  [2]
=C2=A0There is high-stakes credit due diligence each time you start trading=
 on a new exchange. Also though there is just an operational issue: Even if=
 an exchange=E2=80=99s credit is impeccable, if you want to be in a positio=
n to buy $100 million of Bitcoin on that exchange, you have to deposit $100=
 million on that exchange, which means putting it there and not elsewhere.
BitMEX=E2=80=99s post about the flash crash says: =E2=80=9CYes, we are inve=
stigating potential misconduct by traders on our Bitcoin-USDT Spot market (=
Did you even know we offer Spot trading?),=E2=80=9D with a little side-eye =
emoji in that parenthetical. The point is that BitMEX=E2=80=99s spot market=
s are not very important, to BitMEX or its customers or spot Bitcoin trader=
s generally.=C2=A0BitMEX is =E2=80=9CThe OG Exchange for Crypto Derivative =
Trading=E2=80=9D and reports relatively tiny amounts of spot trading relati=
ve to its derivative markets. If you are a market maker trading Bitcoin for=
 dollars (or USDT), you are probably thinking about using your capital and =
technology efficiently to make markets on=C2=A0Binance and Coinbase and hal=
f a dozen other big spot Bitcoin exchanges. BitMEX=E2=80=99s spot market mi=
ght be a bit of an afterthought. And if Bitcoin goes on a drastic sale on B=
itMEX for 10 minutes, you might not have time to get there and buy it.
One possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0as BitMEX says =E2=80=94 is that this was at=
tempted market manipulation. BitMEX is a big crypto=C2=A0derivatives=C2=A0m=
arket with a small crypto spot market attached to it. If you are short some=
 Bitcoin derivatives contract that pays out based on the price of Bitcoin, =
and you sell Bitcoin to drive down the price, you will make money on your s=
hort derivative trade even as you lose money on=C2=A0your spot sales. If yo=
ur derivative contract is very big, and your spot sales are very small =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0because it doesn=E2=80=99t take much to drive down the price in=
 the spot market where you are trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0then this can be a go=
od trade. If that was the idea, though, it didn=E2=80=99t work, in part bec=
ause it=E2=80=99s not like BitMEX=E2=80=99s derivatives settle based on=C2=
=A0its=C2=A0spot market.
  [3]
=C2=A0BitMEX said:
This incident had NO impact on our billion-dollar derivatives markets. It d=
id not move mark prices, and no liquidations were triggered by it because o=
ur indices are independent and battle-tested.
I suppose one other possibility is that it was a fat finger, or the equival=
ent: Someone owned a lot of Bitcoin on BitMEX and wanted to sell them. Ther=
e are good ways to do that: Sell them slowly over time, maybe. Or withdraw =
them from BitMEX and=C2=A0deposit them on another exchange with a larger an=
d more liquid spot market and more market makers, so your big sales will ha=
ve less impact. But that takes time and effort; the Bitcoin market is not k=
nitted together the way the stock market is. If you want to sell all your B=
itcoins all at once on the exchange they happen to be on, that can cost you=
.

