   =20
      Team lift
   =20
 =20

Famously, financial services firms are places where =E2=80=9Cthe assets lea=
ve in the elevators each evening.=E2=80=9D I=C2=A0mean, this is a thing tha=
t you say if you work in financial services. It is flattering to you. It is=
 not always entirely true. If you work in, like, private credit, arguably a=
 lot of the assets are loans. Billions of dollars of loans, which do not ta=
ke the elevator. Perhaps you run a fund, though, and the loans are on the b=
alance sheet of the fund, and your firm=E2=80=99s assets are just you and s=
ome fees.=C2=A0Anyway you=E2=80=99re still pretty important.
How important? One possible answer is, like, =E2=80=9Cif an acquirer wanted=
 to buy your firm, it would pay a premium to the value of the loans=C2=A0in=
 order to get you and your talents and relationships and deal pipeline.=E2=
=80=9D An even more flattering answer is =E2=80=9Cif an acquirer wanted to =
buy your firm, it wouldn=E2=80=99t: It would just hire you, because you are=
 the main asset. The loans would follow, or not, but they=E2=80=99re a comm=
odity and not that important; what matters is the people.=E2=80=9D
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Silas Brown, Paula Seligson=C2=A0and John Sage rep=
orted last week:

Upstart private credit firm Corinthia Global Management approached Barings =
and parent MassMutual about buying certain Barings assets and overseeing so=
me of its portfolios, after poaching more than 20 people from the firm, acc=
ording to people with knowledge of the matter. ...
The new private credit manager also offered to provide portfolio management=
 services to Barings Global Private Finance, which includes Barings=E2=80=
=99 direct lending operations, and assume management of its funds over time=
, subject to investor and regulatory approvals, the person said. The compan=
y also proposed sharing some revenues, the person added.
Discussions haven=E2=80=99t advanced and the two firms are not currently en=
gaged in talks regarding the proposal, the people said.

Rude! This week Barings sued:

Investment manager Barings sued Corinthia Global Management and former empl=
oyees Ian Fowler and Kelsey Tucker after the upstart private credit firm po=
ached more than 20 employees in one of the largest team lifts at an alterna=
tive asset manager in recent years.
The poaching shocked the private credit industry, which has grown to $1.7 t=
rillion in assets under management globally. The industry has expanded quic=
kly as more firms seek exposure to a corner of the loan market that can app=
ear less volatile and offer higher returns, but starting a new asset manage=
r remains difficult given the limited talent pool in the niche.

And the Financial Times notes:

The raid, which one rival to Barings described as =E2=80=9Caggressive=E2=80=
=9D and a tactic they had never seen before, carries a risk that the loans =
Barings currently holds are refinanced by other lenders keen to take advant=
age of the situation.
When private credit firms are willingly put up for sale, it is not unusual =
for a quarter of that firm=E2=80=99s loan book to be refinanced by rivals. =
It is potentially more fraught when a situation is hostile, the rival added=
.
=E2=80=9CTypically this would create a run on the portfolio because anyone =
in those deals would try to refinance them out,=E2=80=9D the person said. =
=E2=80=9CAnd it raises bigger issues of how do [private equity] sponsors fe=
el about them?=E2=80=9D

Barings=E2=80=99 complaint explains how rude it was:

At 5:39 p.m. Eastern time on Friday, March 8 =E2=80=93 after 10:30 at night=
 in London =E2=80=93 the founder of Corinthia, Paul Weightman, emailed Roge=
r Crandall, the chairman and chief executive officer of Barings=E2=80=99 pa=
rent company, Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company (=E2=80=9CMassMut=
ual=E2=80=9D), referencing Mr. Wheeler=E2=80=99s resignation and requesting=
 to arrange a time to speak on Saturday, March 9.
On the morning of March 9, Mr. Weightman again emailed Mr. Crandall threate=
ning that the impending departure of =E2=80=9Cthe senior managers will crea=
te a range of issues for the Barings Private Credit business=E2=80=9D and a=
ttaching an unsolicited term sheet pursuant to which Corinthia sought to as=
sume responsibility for Barings=E2=80=99 entire GPF business, make offers o=
f employment to all employees of the GPF group and have Barings release all=
 of those employees from their restrictive covenants, and purchase the GPF =
portfolio and business for pennies on the dollar. The Corinthia term sheet =
went so far as to provide that Barings would appoint Corinthia as the sub-i=
nvestment advisor for Barings=E2=80=99 managed funds and pay Corinthia a po=
rtion of the management fees earned by Barings on the GPF funds.

Once you have the people, the loans are worth pennies on the dollar. Baring=
s argues that its former employees are breaching their non-solicitation and=
 confidentiality agreements, and you get a sense of how important those agr=
eements are. If the value of the business is just in the employees=E2=80=99=
 knowledge and relationships, and they can take that knowledge and those re=
lationships with them, then what else did Barings own?=C2=A0

