<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US has about a dozen stock exchanges. Each=
 stock trades on each stock exchange. Every so often the price of a stock o=
n one exchange will be slightly lower than the price on another exchange. <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d25vcnRvbi5jb20vYm9va3MvZmxhc2gtYm95cy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb=
674bb8b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">Books</a>=C2=A0have been written about this fact, and peop=
le have made long and lucrative careers from it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we are talking about small differences=C2=
=A0in the grand scheme of things. If I were to tell you =E2=80=9CApple Inc.=
 stock has been trading at $174 per share on the NYSE Arca exchange for the=
 last hour, but it=E2=80=99s been trading at $175 on Nasdaq the whole time,=
=E2=80=9D you would not believe me; that is barely even a coherent sentence=
. For one thing, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0Mi42=
MTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBacb091f6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">there are rules</a> to preve=
nt that. But also, I mean, this stuff is all on computers, and these prices=
 are all visible, and there <em>are </em>people who have lucrative careers =
noticing any differences. If Apple was trading at $174 on Arca and at $175 =
on Nasdaq, those people would buy it on Arca and sell it on Nasdaq, making =
a risk-free instantaneous profit. And so many of them would do this so quic=
kly that the prices would more or less instantly converge.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, at a certain scale =E2=80=94 for the ar=
bitrageurs who make a career of this stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0this is=C2=A0<em>=
not true</em>; there are milliseconds when you can buy at $174.99 one place=
 and sell at $175 another place and make a quick profit. But at human scale=
s it is true enough; there are not=C2=A0<em>hours=C2=A0</em>when=C2=A0you c=
an buy at $174 one place and sell at $175 another.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that=E2=80=99s only true because there are=
 a lot of those arbitrageurs with a lot of capital and fast computers, and =
because a lot of technological and regulatory work has gone into making sur=
e that all of those arbitrageurs can connect to all the stock exchanges and=
 see their prices and move their capital quickly to whatever exchange has c=
heap stock for sale. You could imagine a different system. You could imagin=
e a system where NYSE Arca is downtown and Nasdaq is in midtown and you hav=
e to take a horse and buggy between them to trade, and you can=E2=80=99t us=
e the phone, and there=E2=80=99s just one of you; then maybe prices would d=
iverge by dollars for hours. That=E2=80=99s not too hard to imagine =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it was roughly true 100 years ago, though stocks traded on fewer v=
enues back then =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does not really reflect our modern co=
mputerized markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
zL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMTkvZXhjaGFuZ2UtaW52ZXN0aWdhdGVzLWZsYXNoLWNyYXNoLX=
RoYXQtc2VudC1iaXRjb2luLXRvLTgtOTAwP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0b=
V9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMyMCZ1dG1f=
Y2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe2980c77" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">there=
=E2=80=99s Bitcoin</a>!</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The price of Bitcoin against Tether=E2=80=99s =
USDT stablecoin fell to as low as $8,900 on BitMEX late Monday, while the l=
argest cryptocurrency was trading above $66,000 on rival venues. The price =
of Bitcoin on the exchange quickly recovered and has been trading in-line w=
ith the rest of the market since.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A spokesperson for BitMEX said the company inv=
estigated the incident and found evidence of =E2=80=9Caggressive selling be=
havior involving a very small number of accounts that exceeded expected mar=
ket ranges,=E2=80=9D adding that its systems had operated normally and all =
user funds are safe.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BitMEX is =E2=80=9Cinvestigating potential mis=
conduct by traders on our Bitcoin-USDT Spot market,=E2=80=9D the exchange s=
aid in=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/347548=
66.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9CaXRNRVgvc3RhdHVzLzE3NzAwMzYyMDc0MjQzN=
DQyNzE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfb266fad" target=3D"_blank" title=3D"Link t=
o X post" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">a post</a>=C2=A0on the X social-media platform =
on Tuesday. The exchange does not employ internal market makers and the ord=
ers to sell Bitcoin =E2=80=9Cwere simply too big and frequent for independe=
nt market makers and other traders to react to,=E2=80=9D according to the s=
ame post. The incident had no impact on BitMEX=E2=80=99s derivatives market=
s and no liquidations were triggered by it, the post added.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYmxvY2suY28vcG9zdC8yODMz=
NTgvYml0Y29pbi1mbGFzaC1jcmFzaC1iaXRtZXg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB20c63c83" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">best guess</a> appears to be that this was one big whale, or perhap=
s a few, dumping Bitcoin steadily over a few hours:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSomeone just dumped 400+ =
BTC over 2 hours in 10-50 BTC clips on the XBTUSDT pair on Bitmex eating 30=
%+ slippage. They must've lost $4m+ at least,=E2=80=9D pseudonymous crypto =
community member =E2=80=9Csyq=E2=80=9D wrote. =E2=80=9CI'm guessing that th=
ey're done (for now?). Total volume so far is just shy of 1,000 BTC over 3.=
5 hours with a low of $8,900. Now BitMEX have disabled withdrawals,=E2=80=
=9D they added.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The exceptionally low prices did not persist u=
ninterrupted=C2=A0for hours at a time or anything, but there seems to have =
been a pretty intense 10-minute period of=C2=A0low prices, and in any case =
each=C2=A0<em>time=C2=A0</em>this whale dumped 10 to 50 Bitcoin at a time, =
it got prices far lower than the prints on any other exchange.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, you know, if I were making markets in Bit=
coin on Coinbase, and I noticed that Bitcoin was selling for $8,900 on BitM=
EX, I would simply get myself over to BitMEX and start bidding, like, $9,00=
0 for Bitcoin. That=E2=80=99s free money!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why didn=E2=80=99t anyone? Part of the answer =
is probably that they did; this gap eventually closed, though from BitMEX=
=E2=80=99s posting it seems that the gap closed more because the whale stop=
ped selling than because anyone stepped in to buy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another part of the answer is that crypto =
exchanges are fundamentally different businesses from stock exchanges. In t=
he US, if you buy stock on a stock exchange, you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>sen=
d the money to the stock exchange</em>. You send the money to the seller (a=
nd the seller sends the stock to you) through a clearinghouse; there=E2=80=
=99s one main clearinghouse for all US stock trades, and every exchange and=
 broker is hooked up to it. If you are an arbitrageur looking to buy $100 m=
illion worth of stock, you don=E2=80=99t have to park $100 million at=C2=A0=
<em>each of the 12 exchanges </em>so you can trade on whichever one has the=
 lowest price. You park $100 million at your one brokerage firm, and the br=
oker handles settlement for you wherever you actually execute the trade.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In crypto, it is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDYvdGhlLXNlYy1jb21lcy1mb3ItY3J5cHRvP2=
NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZ=
XdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB94822c92" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the norm</a> for exchanges to hold your m=
oney for you. One thing that this means is that there is a long and comical=
 history of exchanges losing or stealing that money. Another, related thing=
 that it means is that traders have to evaluate the credit risk of exchange=
s: You do not want to deposit $100 million on an exchange that will go and =
lose or steal=C2=A0it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There is high-stakes credit due diligence each time you start tra=
ding on a new exchange. Also though there is just an operational issue: Eve=
n if an exchange=E2=80=99s credit is impeccable, if you want to be in a pos=
ition to buy $100 million of Bitcoin on that exchange, you have to deposit =
$100 million on that exchange, which means putting it there and not elsewhe=
re.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BitMEX=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9CaXR=
NRVgvc3RhdHVzLzE3NzAwMzYyMDc0MjQzNDQyNzE_cz0yMA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCbf=
e0dfc6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">post</a> about the flash crash says: =E2=80=9CYes, we are i=
nvestigating potential misconduct by traders on our Bitcoin-USDT Spot marke=
t (Did you even know we offer Spot trading?),=E2=80=9D with a little side-e=
ye emoji in that parenthetical. The point is that BitMEX=E2=80=99s spot mar=
kets are not very important, to BitMEX or its customers or spot Bitcoin tra=
ders generally.=C2=A0BitMEX <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYml0bWV4LmNvbS8/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBf063eb32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">is</a> =E2=80=9CThe OG Exchange for Crypto Deriva=
tive Trading=E2=80=9D and reports relatively tiny amounts of spot trading r=
elative to its derivative markets. If you are a market maker trading Bitcoi=
n for dollars (or USDT), you are probably thinking about using your capital=
 and technology efficiently to make markets <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYmxvY2suY28vZ=
GF0YS9jcnlwdG8tbWFya2V0cy9zcG90L3RoZS1ibG9jay1sZWdpdGltYXRlLWluZGV4LW1hcmtl=
dC1zaGFyZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe92032b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">on</a>=C2=A0Binance a=
nd Coinbase and half a dozen other big spot Bitcoin exchanges. BitMEX=E2=80=
=99s spot market might be a bit of an afterthought. And if Bitcoin goes on =
a drastic sale on BitMEX for 10 minutes, you might not have time to get the=
re and buy it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0as BitMEX says =
=E2=80=94 is that this was attempted market manipulation. BitMEX is a big c=
rypto=C2=A0<em>derivatives=C2=A0</em>market with a small crypto spot market=
 attached to it. If you are short some Bitcoin derivatives contract that pa=
ys out based on the price of Bitcoin, and you sell Bitcoin to drive down th=
e price, you will make money on your short derivative trade even as you los=
e money on=C2=A0your spot sales. If your derivative contract is very big, a=
nd your spot sales are very small =E2=80=94=C2=A0because it doesn=E2=80=99t=
 take much to drive down the price in the spot market where you are trading=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then this can be a good trade. If that was the idea, though=
, it didn=E2=80=99t work, in part because it=E2=80=99s not like BitMEX=E2=
=80=99s derivatives settle based on=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>spot market.<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0BitMEX <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9CaXRNRVgvc3RhdHVzLzE3NzAwMzYyMDc0=
MjQzNDQyNzE_cz0yMA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDbfe0dfc6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This incident had NO impact on our=
 billion-dollar derivatives markets. It did not move mark prices, and no li=
quidations were triggered by it because our indices are independent and bat=
tle-tested.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose one other possibility is that it was=
 a fat finger, or the equivalent: Someone owned a lot of Bitcoin on BitMEX =
and wanted to sell them. There are good ways to do that: Sell them slowly o=
ver time, maybe. Or withdraw them from BitMEX and=C2=A0deposit them on anot=
her exchange with a larger and more liquid spot market and more market make=
rs, so your big sales will have less impact. But that takes time and effort=
; the Bitcoin market is not knitted together the way the stock market is. I=
f you want to sell all your Bitcoins all at once on the exchange they happe=
n to be on, that can cost you.</p>
