<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Famously, financial services firms are places =
where =E2=80=9Cthe assets leave in the elevators each evening.=E2=80=9D I=
=C2=A0mean, this is a thing that you say if you work in financial services.=
 It is flattering to you. It is not always entirely true. If you work in, l=
ike, private credit, arguably a lot of the assets are loans. Billions of do=
llars of loans, which do not take the elevator. Perhaps you run a fund, tho=
ugh, and the loans are on the balance sheet <em>of the fund</em>, and your =
firm=E2=80=99s assets are just you and some fees.=C2=A0Anyway you=E2=80=99r=
e still pretty important.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How important? One possible answer is, like, =
=E2=80=9Cif an acquirer wanted to buy your firm, it would pay a premium to =
the value of the loans=C2=A0in order to get you and your talents and relati=
onships and deal pipeline.=E2=80=9D An even more flattering answer is =E2=
=80=9Cif an acquirer wanted to buy your firm, it wouldn=E2=80=99t: It would=
 just hire you, because you are the main asset. The loans would follow, or =
not, but they=E2=80=99re a commodity and not that important; what matters i=
s the people.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Silas Brown, Paula Se=
ligson=C2=A0and John Sage <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/34754866.261362/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjQtMDMtMTUvY29yaW50aGlhLWFwcHJvYWNoZWQtYmFyaW5ncy10by1idXktYXNzZXRzLW=
