blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">theory here</a> is that=C2=A0if you are a broadly =
diversified shareholder, and you own stock in Company X, and Company X is d=
oing something that will increase its profits by $100 but will reduce the p=
rofits of your <em>other </em>companies by $110, you should tell Company X =
to knock it off. This theory makes complete sense, though it is often hard =
to know how to implement it: It=E2=80=99s rarely obvious how Company X=E2=
=80=99s actions will affect the total value of=C2=A0<em>all other=C2=A0</em=
>companies. But the Shareholder Commons takes an expansive, imaginative vie=
w. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34754866.261362=
/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVzaGFyZWhvbGRlcmNvbW1vbnMuY29tL3BvdGIyMDI0Lw/607f07ceef4b852=
